metadata.name: Освобождение #34
metadata.description:
Освобождение (Eng.: Release) is the 3rd part of the current series of my Suprematism, textures and colours study.
This work shows the process of colours leaving their constraining shapes, trying to occupy more area. 

——————

Rendering takes around 30-40 seconds at 60 fps, might take longer on older devices.
Press [Arrow Up / Down] to increase / decrease the drawing speed.
Press [1…6] to change the image resolution up to 10k.
Press [C] after the image is rendered to see 2 different states.
Press [S] after the image is rendered to save it.

Created using p5.js.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Sep. 2022.

metadata.name: Petri 1500 v2 QHD  #18
metadata.description:
Petri 1500 is a celebration of reaching 1500 Twitter followers.
As I've grown as an artist what represents that growth but a petri dish, filled with life, finding a way.

There is a bug in the original version that cause display issues on retina & QHD displays. So this version fixes that, is free to all that held a copy at 00:30 14-09-2022 and a few spares for luck.

A sillybration of all things fx(hash) featuring some of my recognisable pallets and primatives
along with something new to me - noise and 'realistic' nature sketches.
All mashed for pure fun.

L to download 1000x1000
S to download 4000x4000
H to download 8000x8000

metadata.name: scratches & circles #68
metadata.description:
first fully coded generative artwork by @ndru_art made with p5.js

project features:
- up to 5 rows of 'scratches' at varying canvas heights & thickness
- scratches generated with random horizontal density and variance
- circles of varying sizes generated within a certain proximity of each row
- 5 different color palettes
- 'narrow scratches' feature defined by rows with a thickness value < 10

minters get 10% of secondary sales

special thanks to Orr Kislev for making his 'sketchy lines' code publicly available

metadata.name: "Oneirism" #37
metadata.description:
Oneirism is a state of abnormal consciousness in which dream-like experiences and hallucinations happen while awake.
This describes the situation I went through learning and writing the algorithm for my first generative project (100 % code)
By learning p5js i discovered a new side of my artistic self and a path i want to follow to make art and express my feelings.
Thanks everyone from my bottom of my heart for helping and guiding me on those difficult last months.

--Features--

Palette : 16 different color schemes
Build : 2 Shapes
Step : "Low" "Medium" "High"
Rotation : 7 types (each type has more than 40 different outcomes)
Fading(Rare) : True or False

Press "s" to save a 1600x2000 PNG

Made with p5js.

Gtsiliakos_art, September 2022

metadata.name: Minima #39
metadata.description:
Minima is a study on focus and color. Playing with the idea of a simple composition of semicircles, either rotated up or down. The focus of the observer is moved with the use of gradual animation in the gradients and occasional circles and/or rectangles connecting the shapes together through color.

The name minima stems from the origins of the composition, mostly taking inspiration from minimalism in its use of a few elements to form a composition greater than the sum of its parts. Less is more, as they say.

The point at the bottom right of the canvas resembles the end of a sentence. Like reading a book, you process the canvas in a similar way, moving from what pops the most to what the least.

As the reader of this canvas I hope you observe what happens to your focus as the colors gradually move across the screen. The animations themselves are looping based on a noised sine wave, which gives them imperfections, imperfections you can observe.

----

Click / Tap on the bar at the bottom of the canvas to open up the GUI, used to export your minima into any format you want. Either .png or .svg. Ready for printing, if you desire.

ps. there might be a secret keyboard shortcut...

----

Minima,
Wouter Missler, 2022,
p5js + webgl.

metadata.name: adrift #165
metadata.description:
Take your entire life, full as it is with the vastness of your lived experiences – and shape it into your cupped hands. Cherish this mesmerising world of yours as you would a ripe summer fruit, and behold at a glance its delicate yet dynamic balance — one change here or there, no matter how microscopic, affects the entire course of your world. 

How will you receive this world – its situations that overwhelm, its sights that awe, the catastrophes, the serenity, its steadfast commitment to the present? Will you look upon all of us here, adrift and fragile together, with love?


Adrift is a project that reminds us to make peace with our world – with all worlds – by stepping back to make space for an all-encompassing perspective.


------------


Created by Jacek Markusiewicz @jMarkusiewicz
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art

Click on the image for resolution options and to save a .png file. Saving higher resolutions may not work in some browsers; in these cases, right-click-save the image. All drawing and geometric methods are written by mrkswcz using javascript, except for the following:

The pseudorandom terrain generation uses Hydraulic-Erosion by Sebastian Lague, inspired by "Reconnaissance" by TENDER x Nat Sarkissian (MIT License).

For finding paths that simulate connections in terrain and potential locations of cities, a C# script was adapted from the article "Pathfinding Algorithms in C#" by Kristian Ekman published in Code Project licensed under The Code Project Open License (CPOL). The code was translated to javascript and simplified for performance.

Many pseudorandom effects are achieved with perlin-simplex by David Guttman and seedrandom by David Bau (both MIT Licenses)

For more information, please see the bundle.js.LICENSE.txt file included in the package.

The "heat death" event is a small tribute to lunarean's fxhash project. The code that generates the disintegration effect interprets a fragment of lunarean's code. Further contributions are its adaptation for 3d transformations and its recursive character that modifies certain parameters over time.

The project uses CPU for calculations and rendering – generating the image requires up to 500MB of free RAM. Testing was performed across browsers and devices, but please make sure it works on your device before minting. Note that there are minor colour-intensity differences between different browsers.

metadata.name: Paper Mandala #31
metadata.description:
A collaboration with P1xelboy and Paper Buddha.
Beautiful paper mandalas made purely with code in Paper Buddha's style.
Features include:
27 different palettes
3 different mandala types (Lotus, Starburst Style 1 and Starburst Style 2)
Four sections of the mandala with one of 10 different pattern types (Dots, Checks, Crosses, Triangles, Stripes, Circles, Polygons, Lazers, Quadrants and Hatching)
4 different direction types of shadow - of varying length
Randomly placed star background
Randomly placed Nebula
Possible Special Pattern Effect with darker stippling pattern
Possible Nirvana Effect where random colors are added to one of either Golden, Silver, Bronze, Blue Moon or Sea Green palettes.

Using only code, this produces a unique output which does take a few seconds to load.
Press "S" to Save your unique Paper Mandala as a 2048 x 2048 JPG
Press "R" for a random shuffle effect - (please wait for reload) - Refresh page to reset

The project works in a responsive browser, so to set up for phone background or watch, resize the browser accordingly and Alt + Print Screen to get an appropriately sized image.

Offered as a Dutch Auction, holders of the first 20 tokens (1-20) will receive additional benefits in the form of utility for future releases in the P1xelboy/Paper Mandala collaboration series. (exact details to be determined)
This utility will remain attached to tokens 1-20 and transfer to the new owner upon subsequent secondary sales.

Uses p5.js and p5.pattern
@p1x3lboy @paperbuddha - September 2022

metadata.name: MOMENT #284
metadata.description:
An endless row of them making up each life. Some poignant, some inspiring, some grievous, some affirming - but most of them a tad boring, a bit generic, almost forgettable like bland fabric. How can a life constructed from such mundanity count for anything? Maybe thanks to the last one, the one that stitches them all together, like a punchline to an absurdist joke.

Generative art written in JavaScript + Canvas with a little bit of help from p5.js.
